We were right there. Souls and bodies squeezed into a church in Texas, that was our last night of life.
Just like this room we are in now, except there were creaking wooden benches, tattered red banners hanging, an organ to my left, a choir behind me, and a baptismal font built into the back wall.
In short, just like this room.
The same strong sense of suspense, the same deep desire for redemption, the same sour sweat in the palms, and at the back row, the same group of absent-minded people.
It was December 31, 1999, that night, as far as I knew, the Second Coming of Christ, the end of the world was approaching.
At that time, I was 12 years old, reaching the age of responsibility.
I realized that Jesus coming back at this time is so unfair, I am about to take responsibility for everything I did before. But when I stop complaining, I think I better tidy up the house quickly.
I try to go to church as much as possible.
I am afraid of the silence around me, just like how people fear noise, only to repeatedly confirm that God did not trick me, coming back early and leaving me behind.
But in case he really came early, I also have a backup plan, which I read from the popular book "End Times Maze".
I saw in the text that if I missed the midnight revelry and was not taken away, I still have one more chance.
I just need to not be labeled as a heretic, defeat demons, overcome plagues, and also defeat anti-Christians.
This will be quite difficult - but I believe I can do it.
But the time for preparation has already passed.
It's already 11:50 at night.
We have 10 minutes left, the pastor asked us to get up from the benches and walk to the altar below, because he wanted us to pray together at the moment of midnight approaching.
So the congregation divided into several groups and went to their designated positions.
The choir is still on the small stage, the church deacons and their wives - I actually prefer to call them the "Baptist bourgeoisie" - sitting in the front row in front of the altar.
You know, in the United States, even on the night of the Second Coming of Christ, there are VIP seats.
Behind the Baptist bourgeoisie, there were the older generation - the young backs of these men and women, bent by the intense sunlight in the cotton fields of East Texas, their rugged faces burnt into a noble brown, just like the clay of East Texas, their dreams and fantasies of a life and world beyond East Texas sometimes more shattered than their backs.
Yes - these men and women are my idols, my stars.
They have waited a lifetime for this moment, just like their medieval ancestors longed for the end of the world, just like my grandmother longed for Oprah Winfrey, which aired on time every day at four o'clock on Channel Eight.
As she walked towards the altar, I quietly slipped behind her, because I was very certain that my grandmother was going to heaven.
I think if I tightly hold her hand during this prayer, I might walk with her.
So I tightened my grip, closed my eyes, listened, and waited.
The prayers grew louder.
The cries in response to the prayers grew louder as well.
The organ started playing, intertwining with the sound of the dirge.
As the heat wave swept through, the sweat in the palms became even more bitter.
My hand clenched tighter, I didn't want to be abandoned by God.
My eyes closed even tighter, I didn't want to see the essence taken away, leaving behind the dregs.
Suddenly, a voice echoed overhead: "Amen."
It's over.
I looked at the clock.
Midnight has passed.
I looked at the elder believers, their savior did not come, they were too proud to show even a hint of disappointment, their faith was too deep, too long, and now it's too late to doubt.
But I felt angry for them.
They were deceived, misled, and confused, yet I still followed them and fell for it together.
I made the same prayer as they did, trying hard to resist the desires in my heart.
Not once, but twice, I plunged into that chilling baptismal pool.
I used to believe.
What should we do now?
I went home and turned on the TV, just in time to catch Peter Jennings announcing the new millennium, with the whole world celebrating the New Year.
I suddenly realized, no matter how I think about it, it's strange - Jesus is supposed to come again and again to different places just because of different time zones.
This made me feel even more uncomfortable in my heart, quite hurt, really.
But on that night, I did not stop believing.
I just believed in one other thing: that "not believing is also possible."
It is very likely that the answers I know are all wrong, and it is very likely that the question itself is wrong.
Now, the once towering peak of faith, with a spring flowing all the way to the foot of the mountain, a spring of questioning, it is destined to become a great river.
All the dramatic stories in my life can be traced back to that night in the church when my savior did not come; the things I was so sure of, if not called "lies", are at least not truths.
Although most of you welcomed the millennium in different ways, I believe you are here because some of you have done the same thing as me, the things that happened after the beginning of the new century, after my mother passed away, after my father left home, after my savior did not come.
I reached out my hands, desperately searching for something to believe in.
