But when the parliamentary work came to a complete standstill, the country was on the brink of disintegration, and the so-called hope and change turned into cruel jokes, I knew that even a political rebirth couldn't save me.
I knelt devoutly before the altar of the American Dream, praying to the great figures of the era, seeking success, seeking money, seeking power.
But every time, when the midnight bell tolls, I open my eyes and see that all these myths have died.
From this grave, I once again begin to search, not because I am brave, but because I know that if I have no faith, I will die.
So I went to another sacred place to worship, Harvard Business School - this time, I knew I couldn't simply accept the redemption offered by the school.
No, I know I have more things to do.
It all started in a dark corner of a crowded party, on a late night in the harsh early winter of Massachusetts, where I and three friends asked a question that many young people with real aspirations have been asking for a long time: "How about we go on a road trip?"
We didn't know where to go or how to get there, but we knew we had to set out.
Because what we have been yearning for all our lives, as Jack Kerouac wrote: "To slip off into the endless night, and disappear into the distant horizon." Go out and see what people across the country are doing.
So even though there were voices of opposition, saying that we were taking too big of a risk and wouldn't gain anything, we still set out.
In the summer of 2013, we traveled 13,000 kilometers across the United States, passing through the dairy farms of Montana, the abandoned urban areas of Detroit, and the swamp wetlands of New Orleans. We found some people there, worked for them, and their small businesses, making achieving goals the bottom line.
After studying at the "West Point of Capitalism," we realized that this idea was truly revolutionary.
This idea spread and eventually grew into a non-profit organization called "Masters in Management Travel Across America," which is also the main reason I can stand on the stage today.
It can spread because we found a strong desire among this generation, a desire to achieve goals and life values.
It can spread because we have found countless entrepreneurs in the corners of the United States, who create jobs, change lives, and just need a little help.
But to be honest, it can spread because I have been tirelessly spreading it. In order to spread this gospel,
There is nothing I wouldn't do to make more people believe that we can heal the wounds of this broken country, relying on one small business at a time.
But it is this process of spreading the gospel that led me to a slightly different gospel, which I am going to share with you today.
It all began about a year ago one evening, at the American Museum of Natural History in New York, attending a Harvard Business School alumni dinner.
Underneath a full-size model of a whale, I sat side by side with the giants of this era, praising their companions and their great achievements.
The room was filled with a sense of pride, as the total assets owned by these individuals amounted to over five trillion US dollars.
We looked down upon all creation, feeling that this was good.
