However, it is not this glaring social inequality that brings tears to my eyes, nor is it these hungry, homeless children, nor the anger towards the 1%, or the compassion towards the 99%.
No, my heart cannot be calm because I finally realize that this country needs a complete transformation, and I am just making minor repairs.
I realized that my story represents a group of people, people who hope that they can help themselves, even if they are penniless; what my organization represents is all the basic, systematic help, but it has never reached Harlem, or the Appalachian Mountains, and the Ninth Ward of New Orleans; my cries represent some voices, those that sound meaningless, unadorned, and out of place.
And this sense of shame, this sense of shame washed over me, just like the shame of sitting in front of the television, watching Peter Jennings announce the new millennium, once, twice, and again.
I was deceived, fooled, and misled,
